enne, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Frankrijk","Mortagne-Au-Perche, Orne, Lower Normandy, France":"Mortagne-au-Perche, Orne, Normandie, Frankrijk","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England"},"en":{"1030–24 July 1078":"1030–24 July 1078","1030–1078":"1030–1078","1035–1088":"1035–1088","1042–1086":"1042–1086","1050–1104":"1050–1104","0992–1074":"0992–1074","1025–1059":"1025–1059","about 1050":"about 1050","1088":"1088","1054":"1054","1086":"1086","1042":"1042","1030":"1030","1074":"1074","1050":"1050","24 July 1078":"24 July 1078","Abt 1074":"about 1074","1104":"1104","1059":"1059","0992":"0992","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","about 1019":"about 1019","1078":"1078","liv. 1054":"1054","Varenne, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, France":"Varenne, Seine-Maritime, Normandy, France","Mortagne-Au-Perche, Orne, Lower Normandy, France":"Mortagne-au-Perche, Orne, Normandy, France","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mortimer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mortemer in Seine-Maritime, France, so called from Old French <i>mort(e)</i> ‘dead’ + <i>mer</i> ‘sea’, probably referring to a stagnant pond or drained swamp.","Irish (of Norman origin): the Norman surname in sense 1 above was taken to Ireland from England in the medieval period, where it has also been adopted by bearers of the Gaelic surnames <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> and <b>ÓMuircheartaigh</b>, commonly Anglicized as <b>McMurty</b> and <b>Mortagh</b>. Compare   McMurdo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mortimore","meanings":["English (Devon; of Norman origin): variant of   Mortimer  ."]},{"name":"McMurdo","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muircheartaich</b>, ‘son of Muircheartach’, a personal name meaning ‘sea-ruler’. In Scotland the name was often lenited to give   McCurdy  . Compare   Murdoch   and   Moriarty  . The name was also used to Anglicize <i>Mac Murchaidh</i> (see   McMorrow  )."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Roger de Mortimer was born in 1030, in Normandy, France, his father, Ranulph de Warenne, was 39 and his mother, Beatrix de Vascoeuil, was 6. He had at least 1 son with Hawise de Valois. He registered for military service in 1054. He died on 24 July 1078, in Mortagne-au-Perche, Orne, Normandy, France, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1030–24 July 1078":"1030–24. juuli 1078","1030–1078":"1030–1078","1035–1088":"1035–1088","1042–1086":"1042–1086","1050–1104":"1050–1104","0992–1074":"0992–1074","1025–1059":"1025–1059","about 1050":"umbes 1050","1088":"1088","1054":"1054","1086":"1086","1042":"1042","1030":"1030","1074":"1074","1050":"1050","24 July 1078":"24. juuli 1078","Abt 1074":"umbes 1074","1104":"1104","1059":"1059","0992":"0992","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","about 1019":"umbes 1019","1078":"1078","liv. 1054":"1054","Varenne, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, France":"Varenne, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Mortagne-Au-Perche, Orne, Lower Normandy, France":"Mortagne-au-Perche, Orne, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England"},"fi":{"1030–24 July 1078":"1030–24. heinäkuuta 1078","1030–1078":"1030–1078","1035–1088":"1035–1088","1042–1086":"1042–1086","1050–1104":"1050–1104","0992–1074":"0992–1074","1025–1059":"1025–1059","about 1050":"noin 1050","1088":"1088","1054":"1054","1086":"1086","1042":"1042","1030":"1030","1074":"1074","1050":"1050","24 July 1078":"24. heinäkuuta 1078","Abt 1074":"noin 1074","1104":"1104","1059":"1059","0992":"0992","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","about 1019":"noin 1019","1078":"1078","liv. 1054":"1054","Varenne, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, France":"Varenne, Seine-Maritime, Normandie, Ranska","Mortagne-Au-Perche, Orne, Lower Normandy, France":"Mortagne-au-Perche, Orne, Normandie, Ranska","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, England"},"fr":{"1030–24 July 1078":"1030–24 juillet 1078","1030–1078":"1030–1078","1035–1088":"1035–1088","1042–1086":"1042–1086","1050–1104":"1050–1104","0992–1074":"0992–1074","1025–1059":"1025–1